    "created_at": "2011-06-24T04:56:53Z",
    "updated_at": "2011-06-24T04:56:53Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "After some testing, Brian discovered that ipcontroller's use of multiprocessing means that ipcontroller actually requires _distribute_, not just setuptools.\n\nsetuptools will write this ipcontroller script:\n\n``` python\n\n#!c:\\Python27\\python.exe\n# EASY-INSTALL-ENTRY-SCRIPT: 'ipython==0.11.dev','console_scripts','ipcontroller'\n__requires__ = 'ipython==0.11.dev'\nimport sys\nfrom pkg_resources import load_entry_point\n\nsys.exit(\n   load_entry_point('ipython==0.11.dev', 'console_scripts', 'ipcontroller')()\n)\n```\n\nwhereas distribute writes:\n\n``` python\n\n#!c:\\Python27\\python.exe\n# EASY-INSTALL-ENTRY-SCRIPT: 'ipython==0.11.dev','console_scripts','ipcontroller'\n__requires__ = 'ipython==0.11.dev'\nimport sys\nfrom pkg_resources import load_entry_point\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    sys.exit(\n        load_entry_point('ipython==0.11.dev', 'console_scripts', 'ipcontroller')()\n    )\n```\n\nThe `if __name__ == '__main__'` is critical, because without it, multiprocessing will start the Controller in _every subprocess_, creating infinite children.\n\nSo, should we depend on distribute instead of setuptools?\n"
  },
